Below is an example implementation of `React.Context` using [TypeScript](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/home.html) and [hooks](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-intro.html).

See [React - Context](https://reactjs.org/docs/context.html) for more info.

```
// Dependencies.
import React, {createContext, useState, SetStateAction, Dispatch} from &#39;react&#39;

// App Context.
interface AppContext {

  // Data.
  menuIsOpen: boolean
  sideIsOpen: boolean

  // Functions.
  setMenuIsOpen: Dispatch&lt;SetStateAction&lt;boolean&gt;&gt;
  setSideIsOpen: Dispatch&lt;SetStateAction&lt;boolean&gt;&gt;

}

// Context.
export const Context = createContext&lt;AppContext&gt;({

  // Data.
  menuIsOpen: false,
  sideIsOpen: false,

  // Functions.
  setMenuIsOpen: open =&gt; {},
  setSideIsOpen: open =&gt; {}

})

// Provider
export const Provider: React.FC&lt;{}&gt; = props =&gt; {

  // State.
  const [menuIsOpen, setMenuIsOpen] = useState(false)
  const [sideIsOpen, setSideIsOpen] = useState(false)

  // Data.
  const data = {menuIsOpen, sideIsOpen}

  // Functions.
  const functions = {setMenuIsOpen, setSideIsOpen}

  // Value.
  const value = {...data, ...functions}

  // ..
  return &lt;Context.Provider value={value}&gt;{props.children}&lt;/Context.Provider&gt;

}

For `initialState` you want to define the same structure/shape as used in `AppProvider `, as TypeScript infers the whole context type from the given initial value. So the type of the initial value determines the context shape that consuming components are able to use.

In your sample, the `AppProvider` context value is incompatible to `initialState`. Also `initialState` types are too &quot;wide&quot; to be useful for consuming components. E.g. `Object` would mean, you expect an Object constructor to be the `state` (not really what you want). With `setState: () =&gt; {}`, components using the context would not be able to invoke this function with a state argument, as the function type pretends to be parameterless.

I assume here, that the general state shall look like this (and omit the additional array wrapper you used in `AppProvider`):
```
{ isMenuOpen: boolean; isSideOpen: boolean }
```
Then an initial state with proper types would be:
```
const initialState = {
  // your state defaults
  state: { isMenuOpen: false, isSideOpen: false }, 
  // noop
  setState: (state: { isMenuOpen: boolean; isSideOpen: boolean }) =&gt; {}
};
```
`AppProvider`:
```
export const AppProvider = (props: IProviderProps) =&gt; {
  const [state, setState] = useState({ isMenuOpen: false, isSideOpen: false });

  return (
    &lt;AppContext.Provider value={{ state, setState }}&gt;
      {props.children}
    &lt;/AppContext.Provider&gt;
  );
};
```

If you want to have it the clean way with own state type and used React type in `useState`, you can implement it like this:
```
import { createContext, useState, Dispatch, SetStateAction } from &quot;react&quot;;

type MyState = {
  isMenuOpen: boolean;
  isSideOpen: boolean;
};

type ContextValue = {
  state: MyState;
  // the type when you hover over setState in AppProvider
  setState: Dispatch&lt;SetStateAction&lt;MyState&gt;&gt;;
};

const initialState: ContextValue = {
  // your state defaults
  state: { isMenuOpen: false, isSideOpen: false },
  // noop
  setState: (state: { isMenuOpen: boolean; isSideOpen: boolean }) =&gt; {}
};
```

